erve comfort rather than challenge oppression. Drawing on the legacy of figures like Martin Luther King Jr. and liberation theologians, he argues that faith must once again become prophetic, willing to speak truth to power and call out racial sin. Bradley’s chapters provide a moral lens that reframes Ferguson as a spiritual crisis about how Americans live out their professed values of justice and equality."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"l27htfCm_q6i6RRHC_4eTg,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"l27htfCm_q6i6RRHC_4eTg,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"l27htfCm_q6i6RRHC_4eTg","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",1],"o":"start","l":476,"c":"Anthony Bradley approaches race and justice from a theological and moral perspective, arguing that Christian faith must confront systemic racism, not just individual sin. In his author’s note and early chapters, he critiques both white evangelicals and secular activists for failing to acknowledge how deeply race and power intersect in American life. Bradley insists that the Church has a responsibility to address injustice because racism violates the Christian doctrine of "},{"t":"t","i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",477],"o":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",476],"l":9,"c":"Imago Dei","b":[{"t":"a","x":"l27htfCm_q6i6RRHC_4eTg","l":"","i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",1317],"s":{"i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",477],"a":"b"},"e":{"i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",486],"a":"b"},"a":["i"]}]},{"t":"t","i":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",486],"o":["6OG7cJGb3FL5",485],"l":831,"c":"—the belief that all people are made in God’s image. He criticizes how many churches have retreated into a privatized, apolitical faith that values personal salvation over social transformation, calling this retreat a betrayal of the Gospel’s ethical demands. For Bradley, the moral failures that led to moments like Ferguson are not just political problems but spiritual ones: they expose how religion can be used to preserve comfort rather than challenge oppression. Drawing on the legacy of figures like Martin Luther King Jr. and liberation theologians, he argues that faith must once again become prophetic, willing to speak truth to power and call out racial sin. Bradley’s chapters provide a moral lens that reframes Ferguson as a spiritual crisis about how Americans live out their professed values of justice and equality.","b":[]},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461977,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8083-b3aa-c581e548732a":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8083-b3aa-c581e548732a","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":2,"type":"divider","crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"NdYpgB5NgZf5-u-CnIlvFg,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"NdYpgB5NgZf5-u-CnIlvFg,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"NdYpgB5NgZf5-u-CnIlvFg","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461979,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8089-a0d8-f8ba02a8bf51":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8089-a0d8-f8ba02a8bf51","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":4,"type":"sub_sub_header","properties":{"title":[["Yamiche Alcindor, “Amid Weekend of Protests, ‘World Is Watching’ Ferguson” (USA Today, Oct. 11, 2014)",[["b"]]]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"laAFkIK87cGNZYQik2_TXw,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"laAFkIK87cGNZYQik2_TXw,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"laAFkIK87