ess exhaustion but also a deep sense of purpose, insisting that their demonstrations are acts of dignity, not disorder. Alcindor’s piece captures the transformation of Ferguson from a site of tragedy into a sustained movement, showing how moral witness and media attention converged to hold American democracy accountable."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"LUlFxqSZgP9TEFawvLBcgA,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"LUlFxqSZgP9TEFawvLBcgA,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"LUlFxqSZgP9TEFawvLBcgA","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",1],"o":"start","l":41,"c":"Yamiche Alcindor’s article documents the "},{"t":"t","i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",42],"o":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",41],"l":21,"c":"Weekend of Resistance","b":[{"t":"a","x":"LUlFxqSZgP9TEFawvLBcgA","l":"","i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",1301],"s":{"i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",42],"a":"b"},"e":{"i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",63],"a":"b"},"a":["i"]}]},{"t":"t","i":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",63],"o":["jN_Bb0_G8kvc",62],"l":1238,"c":"—a large, organized series of protests held two months after Michael Brown’s death. Alcindor emphasizes how Ferguson had become a global focal point by this time, with thousands of protesters, clergy, students, and national figures like Cornel West joining local residents in calling for accountability. Her reporting highlights both the persistence of grassroots organizing and the continued militarization of police responses, describing tear gas, riot gear, and heavy surveillance. The headline phrase “the world is watching” reflects the new reality of public protest in a digital age, where cameras, livestreams, and social media placed Ferguson under constant scrutiny. Alcindor’s tone contrasts sharply with early media portrayals of Ferguson as chaotic or lawless; instead, she presents a disciplined, determined community grounded in faith and solidarity. She includes the voices of young activists who express exhaustion but also a deep sense of purpose, insisting that their demonstrations are acts of dignity, not disorder. Alcindor’s piece captures the transformation of Ferguson from a site of tragedy into a sustained movement, showing how moral witness and media attention converged to hold American democracy accountable.","b":[]},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461981,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8075-8cb4-e3bfc67da4d2":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8075-8cb4-e3bfc67da4d2","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":2,"type":"divider","crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"6-31y-Go6_Q3m7AfbT3aBQ,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"6-31y-Go6_Q3m7AfbT3aBQ,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"6-31y-Go6_Q3m7AfbT3aBQ","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461983,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-80d6-82d6-c4b91ca027f2":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-80d6-82d6-c4b91ca027f2","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":4,"type":"sub_sub_header","properties":{"title":[["Tef Poe and Ashley Yates, “This Is What You Call a Movement” (Oct. 17, 2014)",[["b"]]]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"u9U7xgmCC984tp5gmz-xfw,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"u9U7xgmCC984tp5gmz-xfw,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"u9U7xgmCC984tp5gmz-xfw","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["A0gYNH6CvKWP",1],"o":"start","l":76,"c":"Tef Poe and Ashley Yates, “This Is What You Call a Movement” (Oct. 17, 2014)","b":[{"t":"a","x":"u9U7xgmCC984tp5gmz-xfw","l":"","i":["A0gYNH6CvKWP",77],"s":{"i":["A0gYNH6CvKWP",1],"a":"b"},"e":{"i":"end","a":"b"},"a":["b"]}]},{"t":"e","b":[]}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461984,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-80a2-8df0-e8605a4cb39e":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-80a2-8df0-e8605a4cb39e","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":3,"type":"text","properties":{"title":[["In their public statement, Ferguson organizers Tef Poe and Ashley Yates directly address misconceptions about the protests and assert ownership over their movement. They reject the claim that Ferguson lacked leadership, arguing instead that leadership was decentralized, youth-driven, and intentionally different from the hierarchical structures of the 1960s civil rights era. Their tone is assertive and unapologetic, insisting that local residents—not national organizations or outside commentators—should define the direction of the struggle. Poe and Yates demand concrete reforms: independent investigations into police killings, demilitarization of police forces, and community control over law enforcement. Their message emphasizes authenticity and intersectionality, acknowledging the central roles of women, queer activists, and ordinary residents. The statement’s language—“we don’t need permission to fight for our lives”—captures the urgency of survival and the emotional power behind Ferguson’s protests. It represents a generational declaration that Black resistance would no longer depend on respectability politics or traditional leadership approval. Poe and Yates position Ferguson as the birthplace of a new political culture rooted in self-determination, digital organizing, and an unfiltered demand for systemic change."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"-OUsuM-3PgYDZHFWvRz5iw,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"-OUsuM-3PgYDZHFWvRz5iw,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"-OUsuM-3PgYDZHFWvRz5iw","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["ePXU8X5twit0",1],"o":"start","l":1338,"c":"In their public statement, Ferguson organizers Tef Poe and Ashley Yates directly address misconceptions about the protests and assert ownership over their movement. They reject the claim that Ferguson lacked leadership, arguing instead that leadership was decentralized, youth-driven, and intentionally different from the hierarchical structures of the 1960s civil rights era. Their tone is assertive and unapologetic, insisting that local residents—not national organizations or outside commentators—should define the direction of the struggle. Poe and Yates demand concrete reforms: independent investigations into police killings, demilitarization of police forces, and community control over law enforcement. Their message emphasizes authenticity and intersectionality, acknowledging the central roles of women, queer activists, and ordinary residents. The statement’s language—“we don’t need permission to fight for our lives”—captures the urgency of survival and the emotional power behind Ferguson’s protests. It represents a generational declaration that Black resistance would no longer depend on respectability politics or traditional leadership approval. Poe and Yates position Ferguson as the birthplace of a new political culture rooted in self-determination, digital organizing, and an unfiltered demand for systemic change."},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461985,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8048-80cc-c6822725669a":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8048-80cc-c6822725669a","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":2,"type":"divider","crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"X_iHEZj4DhzZZJIPQ-ClLQ,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"X_iHEZj4DhzZZJIPQ-ClLQ,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"X_iHEZj4DhzZZJIPQ-ClLQ","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461987,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8037-af2a-d2b098c6f7c0":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8037-af2a-d2b098c6f7c0","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":4,"type":"sub_sub_header","properties":{"title":[["Video: “Ferguson: The Coming of Age of a Movement” (PBS / Washington Post)",[["b"]]]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"X1dZgf_A8QH9xuKybQNfJw,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"X1dZgf_A8QH9xuKybQNfJw,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"X1dZgf_A8QH9xuKybQNfJw","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["cgWev-4YLthl",1],"o":"start","l":74,"c":"Video: “Ferguson: The Coming of Age of a Movement” (PBS / Washington Post)","b":[{"t":"a","x":"X1dZgf_A8QH9xuKybQNfJw","l":"","i":["cgWev-4YLthl",75],"s":{"i":["cgWev-4YLthl",1],"a":"b"},"e":{"i":"end","a":"b"},"a":["b"]}]},{"t":"e","b":[]}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461987,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-8025-8242-d31880de37ec":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-8025-8242-d31880de37ec","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":3,"type":"text","properties":{"title":[["The short documentary visually captures the human, emotional, and organizational dimensions of the Ferguson uprising. Through footage of protests, interviews, and social media clips, the film follows activists such as Brittany Packnett, DeRay Mckesson, and Tef Poe as they describe their political awakening. The opening scenes—cellphone videos of armored police vehicles, tear gas, and chants of “Hands Up, Don’t Shoot”—illustrate the militarization of law enforcement and the community’s fear and grief. Yet the documentary also emphasizes growth and transformation: how ordinary residents became organizers and leaders through necessity. One of the most striking themes is the democratization of media. Social platforms like Twitter and livestreaming gave protesters the ability to narrate events themselves, bypassing the distortions of national news outlets. Brittany Packnett’s statement, “We are the ones we’ve been waiting for,” encapsulates the film’s central message—that Ferguson was not simply a reaction to one death but a collective awakening to long-standing injustice. The film’s raw imagery and first-person testimony give emotional depth to the readings, turning written accounts of struggle into visible acts of resistance and hope."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"ZWjRvPExm6ClkVvgBhhktg,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"ZWjRvPExm6ClkVvgBhhktg,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"ZWjRvPExm6ClkVvgBhhktg","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["thAXOGb45RVQ",1],"o":"start","l":1251,"c":"The short documentary visually captures the human, emotional, and organizational dimensions of the Ferguson uprising. Through footage of protests, interviews, and social media clips, the film follows activists such as Brittany Packnett, DeRay Mckesson, and Tef Poe as they describe their political awakening. The opening scenes—cellphone videos of armored police vehicles, tear gas, and chants of “Hands Up, Don’t Shoot”—illustrate the militarization of law enforcement and the community’s fear and grief. Yet the documentary also emphasizes growth and transformation: how ordinary residents became organizers and leaders through necessity. One of the most striking themes is the democratization of media. Social platforms like Twitter and livestreaming gave protesters the ability to narrate events themselves, bypassing the distortions of national news outlets. Brittany Packnett’s statement, “We are the ones we’ve been waiting for,” encapsulates the film’s central message—that Ferguson was not simply a reaction to one death but a collective awakening to long-standing injustice. The film’s raw imagery and first-person testimony give emotional depth to the readings, turning written accounts of struggle into visible acts of resistance and hope."},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461988,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925","last_edited_by_table":"notion_user","last_edited_by_id":"222d872b-594c-8128-886d-0002585be925"},"role":"editor"}},"286a8836-e820-80d9-a155-d591b97ee45d":{"spaceId":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","value":{"value":{"id":"286a8836-e820-80d9-a155-d591b97ee45d","space_id":"8c4a8836-e820-8133-9c30-00030263b38c","version":2,"type":"divider","crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"3bl75LSP54Ypqg3LS5MxVg,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"3bl75LSP54Ypqg3LS5MxVg,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"3bl75LSP54Ypqg3LS5MxVg","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_for