out race and state power. Bradley gives a theological critique that repositions racial justice as a moral duty for faith communities. Alcindor captures the organized, global scope of the movement, while Poe and Yates assert a new political identity for young Black activists. The documentary ties them all together, showing how technology transformed both the visibility and the structure of social movements. Across these works, Ferguson emerges as a site of both mourning and rebirth—a moment where grief, faith, and digital media converged to redefine what protest, leadership, and citizenship mean in twenty-first-century America."]]},"crdt_data":{"title":{"r":"X3nwE6Yh0nhnF0dKb271-A,\"start\",\"end\"","n":{"X3nwE6Yh0nhnF0dKb271-A,\"start\",\"end\"":{"s":{"x":"X3nwE6Yh0nhnF0dKb271-A","i":[{"t":"s"},{"t":"t","i":["yew9PlOOa-ql",1],"o":"start","l":884,"c":"Together, these sources construct a layered understanding of Ferguson as both an event and a turning point in contemporary American activism. Lowery provides a journalist’s insider view of how Ferguson reshaped national media and revived questions about race and state power. Bradley gives a theological critique that repositions racial justice as a moral duty for faith communities. Alcindor captures the organized, global scope of the movement, while Poe and Yates assert a new political identity for young Black activists. The documentary ties them all together, showing how technology transformed both the visibility and the structure of social movements. Across these works, Ferguson emerges as a site of both mourning and rebirth—a moment where grief, faith, and digital media converged to redefine what protest, leadership, and citizenship mean in twenty-first-century America."},{"t":"e"}],"l":""},"c":[]}}}},"crdt_format_version":1,"created_time":1759944461991,"last_edited_time":1759944462005,"parent_id":"286a8836-e820-80c2-be77-dca4e900eaf0","parent_table":"block","alive":true,"created_by_table":"notion_user","created_by_id